Name: notificationPermission

Type: function

Syntax: notificationPermission()

Summary:
Returns the current notification permission state for the application.

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: mac, windows, linux

Platforms: desktop

Example:
-- Check permission before posting a notification
if notificationPermission() is "granted" then
    showNotification "Hello" "Notifications are working."
else
    requestNotificationPermission
end if

Example:
-- Show different UI based on current state
switch notificationPermission()
    case "granted"
        set the label of button "Notifications" to "Enabled"
    case "denied"
        set the label of button "Notifications" to "Blocked"
    default
        set the label of button "Notifications" to "Not set"
end switch

Value:
<notificationPermission> returns one of the following strings:

- "granted" — the application is allowed to show notifications.
- "denied" — the user has blocked notifications for this application.
- "unknown" — the system has not yet been asked, or the state cannot be
  determined. Use <requestNotificationPermission> to prompt the user.

Description:
Use <notificationPermission> to read the current permission state
synchronously, without triggering a system prompt.

On Windows and Linux, notifications are always permitted and this
function always returns "granted". On macOS and iOS, the value reflects
the current setting in System Settings / Settings → Notifications. On
Android 13 and later, it reflects the runtime permission state.

To request permission and receive an asynchronous callback, use
<requestNotificationPermission> instead.

References: requestNotificationPermission (command),
showNotification (command), notificationPermissionGranted (message),
notificationPermissionDenied (message)

Tags: notifications
